{"schemaVersion":{"major":0,"minor":3,"patch":0},"identifier":{"interfaceLanguage":"swift","url":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Signals"},"kind":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Signals in Godot are used by objects to post interesting events that are"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"taking place, and can be used by users to easily add behavior and react","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"to changes.","type":"text"}],"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot"]]},"primaryContentSections":[{"content":[{"type":"heading","anchor":"Overview","level":2,"text":"Overview"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Objects in Godot can emit signals, these are notification about certain"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"events taking place in the objects that can be observed externally."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"In SwiftGodot, there is a convenient interface to connect to a signal, as well","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"as a low-level framework to manually connect to signals and a mechanism to"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"define your own signals."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Objects that emit signals typically do so by using the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Object\/emitSignal"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"function which takes as a parameter the "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/StringName","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" of the signal as well"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"as an optional list of additional arguments.   And users can connect to those"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"signals and direct a method to be invoked when they are raised.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"anchor":"Using-Signals","text":"Using Signals","level":2,"type":"heading"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To connect to a signal, find the signal that you want to connect to in your"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"type, and then call the connect method on it."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"For example, to connect to the "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Node\/ready","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" signal, you call its connect"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"method, like this:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":null,"code":["func setupBot (robot: Node) {","    robot.ready.connect {","        print (\"The robot's node is ready\")","    }","}"]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Since signals in Godot can include parameters, each signal in Godot"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"surfaces a connect method that takes as an argument a function with the"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"precise signature that it will be invoked with.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"If you want to stop receiving notifications, you can disconnect from the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"object, to do so, you must keep around the token returned by the connect"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"method, like this:"}]},{"code":["class Demo: Node {","    var readyToken: Object","","    func setup () {","        readyToken = robot.ready.connect {","            print (\"Ready\")","        }","    }","","    func teardown () {","        robot.ready.disconnect (readyToken)","    }","}"],"syntax":null,"type":"codeListing"},{"level":2,"text":"One-shot signals","type":"heading","anchor":"One-shot-signals"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"One common idiom in Godot code is to wait for a signal to be raised before","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"continuing execution.   For example, you might want to wait for a timeout"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"or an action.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In those cases, you can await the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"emitted"},{"type":"text","text":" property of the generated"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"signal, like this:","type":"text"}]},{"code":["func waitTimer (scene: SceneTree) {","    \/\/ Creates the timer","    let timer = scene.createTimer (timeSec: 3)","","    \/\/ Wait until the timer fires","    await timer.timeout.emitted","","    print (\"Done waiting!\")","}"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":null},{"text":"Declaring your own Signals","anchor":"Declaring-your-own-Signals","type":"heading","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"It is also possible to define your own signals to broadcast them, both"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"to other Swift component as well as using them in Godot or from the"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"Godot Scripting language.","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Signals belong to your class, so you need to declare those once per class,"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"and then every instance of your class can emit them.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This process is currently a little bit more elaborate than consuming them,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"but I am hoping that with the upcoming reflection support in Swift, or"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"with Swift Macros, I can simplify this process."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Signals can have zero or more parameters, and you will need to declare","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"the parameters that your signal consumes, any potential return values (these","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"are quite unusual, but the API supports it), and the name of your signal."}]},{"type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Signals with no parameters","anchor":"Signals-with-no-parameters"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The following example shows how to declare a a signal named "},{"code":"burp","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" that","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"is emitted by your code:","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"code":["class Demo: Node3D {","    static burpSignalName = StringName (\"burp\")","","    \/\/ This idiom is the equivalent of a class constructor for Swift","    static var initClass: Void = {","        let classInfo = ClassInfo<Demo> (name: \"Demo\")","","        classInfo.registerSignal (burpSignal)","    }()","","    \/\/ Constructor showing how to initialize the class and declare the signal","    required init () {","        super.init ()","        let _ = Demo.initClass","    }","","    \/\/ Convenience method to emit the signal","    public func emitBurp () {","        let result = emitSignal (signal: burpSignalName)","    }","}"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":null},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"We start by declaring the ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/StringName"},{"type":"text","text":" for the signal that we are"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"declaring, in this case ","type":"text"},{"code":"burp","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":".  Since signals are registered for classes,"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"we use an idiom to initialize the class once.   This will use ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ClassInfo","type":"reference"},{"text":"","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"to declare our signal, and we register it there.   Since this is a signal"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"that takes no arguments, merely calling "},{"code":"ClassInfo\/registerSignal","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" is enough."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The method ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"emitBurp"},{"type":"text","text":" shows what you need to do to emit the signal from"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"your code."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"result"},{"text":" variable contains a status code that you can inspect.  If there","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"is a mistake in your declaration, or how you emitted the signal, the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"result will describe the reason.","type":"text"}]},{"text":"Signals with parameters","type":"heading","level":3,"anchor":"Signals-with-parameters"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Signals that include parameters require a little bit more of work, both","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"to declare them and to emit them.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Signals can only carry parameters that can be represented by the Godot"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Variant"},{"text":" type.   While it can not represent all possible Swift objects,","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"it can pass all the Godot objects and some core types like integers, floats","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"and strings around."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To register a signal with parameters, you create an array of "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PropInfo","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"elements, one for each parameters of your function.   This information","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"contains information that is not only used at runtime, but can be shown","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"to the user in the Godot editor.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The following example shows how to register a signal that passes a"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"string argument:","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","code":["static let printerSignal = StringName (\"printer\")","","\/\/ This idiom is the equivalent of a class constructor for Swift","static var initClass: Bool = {","    let classInfo = ClassInfo<Demo> (name: \"Demo\")","","    let printArgs = [","        PropInfo(","            propertyType: .string,","            propertyName: StringName (\"text\"),","            className: \"Demo\",","            hint: .flags,","            hintStr: \"Text\",","            usage: .propertyUsageDefault)","    ]","    classInfo.registerSignal (name: Demo.printerSignal, arguments: printArgs)","    return true","}"],"syntax":null},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"See the documentation for ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PropInfo"},{"type":"text","text":" for more information on the"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"meaning of the parameters.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Emitting this signal is also a little bit different.   Unlike our previous"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"example, it is necessary to wrap every argument into a "},{"code":"Variant","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" instance."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This is how we would emit that:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","code":["func emitPrint (text: String) {","    let result = emitSignal(signal: SpinningCube.printerSignal, Variant (text))","}"],"syntax":null},{"level":2,"type":"heading","text":"Using the low-level Signal framework","anchor":"Using-the-low-level-Signal-framework"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"While SwiftGodot provides a convenient way of connecting to objects,","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"if you need to connect to objects that are not included in the binding","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"or you want to implement additional semantics, you can always use the","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"low-level API for connecting signals."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"To connect a signal directly, you use the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Object\/connect"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"method.   The first parameter is the "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/StringName"},{"type":"text","text":" describing the signal"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"and the second one is refenrece to the method to invoke.  The "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Callable","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"is a pair of the object instance and the ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/StringName","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":" of the method to invoke."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"For example:","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let callable = Callable(object: self, method: StringName (\"MyCallback\"))","object.connect(signal: \"some_signal\", callable)"],"syntax":null},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This would call a method registered with Godot under the name "},{"code":"MyCallback","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"on the provided instance when the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"object"},{"text":" raises the ","type":"text"},{"code":"some_signal","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"To surface a Swift method to Godot, and thus be able to reference it with","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"a StringName, you would use a similar method to register a signal:","type":"text"}]},{"syntax":null,"type":"codeListing","code":["func mySwiftCallback () {","   print (\"MyCallback has been invoked!\")","}","","func setup () {","    classInfo.registerMethod(","        name: \"MyCallback\", ","        flags: .default, ","        returnValue: nil, ","        arguments: [], ","        function: Demo.mySwiftCallback)","}"]}],"kind":"content"}],"metadata":{"role":"article","roleHeading":"Article","modules":[{"name":"SwiftGodot"}],"title":"Signals"},"sections":[],"variants":[{"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}],"paths":["\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/signals"]}],"references":{"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Node/ready":{"title":"ready","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Node\/ready","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/node\/ready","kind":"symbol","abstract":[{"text":"To connect to this signal, reference this property and call the","type":"text"}],"role":"symbol","fragments":[{"text":"var","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"ready","kind":"identifier"},{"text":": ","kind":"text"},{"preciseIdentifier":"s:10SwiftGodot12SimpleSignalC","text":"SimpleSignal","kind":"typeIdentifier"}],"type":"topic"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Callable":{"abstract":[],"type":"topic","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Callable","navigatorTitle":[{"text":"Callable","kind":"identifier"}],"role":"symbol","title":"Callable","fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"class"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"text":"Callable","kind":"identifier"}],"kind":"symbol","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/callable"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/ClassInfo":{"abstract":[{"text":"Provides support to expose Swift methods and signals to the Godot runtime, making it callable","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"from its runtime and scripting language."}],"title":"ClassInfo","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/classinfo","kind":"symbol","type":"topic","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ClassInfo","fragments":[{"text":"class","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"ClassInfo","kind":"identifier"}],"navigatorTitle":[{"kind":"identifier","text":"ClassInfo"}],"role":"symbol"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/PropInfo":{"url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/propinfo","type":"topic","title":"PropInfo","navigatorTitle":[{"kind":"identifier","text":"PropInfo"}],"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"PropInfo structures describe arguments to signals, and methods as well as return values from methods."}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PropInfo","kind":"symbol","role":"symbol","fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"struct"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"text":"PropInfo","kind":"identifier"}]},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/StringName":{"type":"topic","kind":"symbol","role":"symbol","fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"class"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"StringName","kind":"identifier"}],"navigatorTitle":[{"kind":"identifier","text":"StringName"}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/StringName","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/stringname","title":"StringName","abstract":[]},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot":{"kind":"symbol","title":"SwiftGodot","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Framework to write Godot Game Extensions using the Swift Programming Language."}],"type":"topic","role":"collection"}}}